Water pH logger

Monitoring the Renaturation process of the Aa river in Münster Unmmanned Aerial Systems

senseBox group

July 12, 2018

Introduction

The pH logger objective was used to assess the water surface temperature at the study area site, where the river Aa had undergone renaturation, and at two other sites where the river was not renatured yet. The logger was equipped with a pH electrode and a LCD screen to display the values. The electrode is not part of the senseBox equipment, but can be squired as a low-cost alternative to high-quality field sensors. Figure 1 shows the logger built and in use on the study area.

Fig. 1: Water pH logger on the field

pH stands for Hydrogen Potential and it is an important variable to characterize the quality of a certain water. It is a measure representing the hydrogen-ion concentration (activity) of a solution, in other words, it describes how acid or basic a water is (Ritz & Colins, 2008). The pH of the water in a river can tell a lot about their environmental status, and its ability to host healthy fauna and flora, as well as being an indication of possible pollution sources.

Materials

To build this logger, as well as the other loggers for the current project, we made use of the senseBox:edu toolkit. For this project, we used the previous senseBox version, therefore, the documentation on the site might have changed, but is still supported. The senseBox used is based on an Arduino Genuino Uno board, on which, an user-friendly and easy-to-learn programming language can be used to configure the logger. The code used for this particular logger can be found on the section Arduino code.

The materials to build the logger are listed below:

  • senseBox:edu box items:
    • Arduino Genuino Uno board
    • Breadboard
    • Jumper wires
    • USB cable
    • AA battery holder
  • SKU:FIT0348 pH electrode
  • DFR0009 LCD Keypad shield
  • Calibration liquids: Buffer solutions pH 4 and pH 7
  • Distilled water
  • 6 AA batteries

To use the pH logger on the field, it is first recommended to do a Calibration of its values, to improve its accuracy. Also, it is recommended to use distilled to clean the electrode between measurements, to avoid any contamination from the electrode to the biffer liquid where it is preserved, and to avoid missleading results from the next solution to evaluate.

Calibration

The pH electrode should be calibrated to improve the accuracy of its outcomes. To perform the calibration, two buffer solutions are needed, with known pH. It is recommended to work with a liquid of pH 4 and another of pH 7. To calibrate the electrode, we first introduce it on the pH 7 solution, and check the value that the electrode gives. We then add a calibration offset to the code uploaded onto the Arduino Genuino Uno board, depending on wether the value is higher or lower than 7. After cleaning the electrode we distilled water, we introduce it on the pH 4 solution and check the value displayed. If there is still an offset, one should try to find an optimal value that allows the measurements on both solutions have the minimal error possible, while setting the final offset on the code.

Arduino code

NOTE: The code includes the offset obtained from the calibration procedure and should be updated every time a calibration is performed.

/* 
 * pH data logger saves to an SD card with a timestamp for each record
 * 
 * senseBox Group
 * Unmanned Aerial Systems
 * Geospatial Technologies MSc.
 * 
 * Institute for Geoinformatics, University of Muenster
 * May. 2018
*/
#include <LiquidCrystal.h>
#define SensorPin A0    // pH meter Analog output an Arduino Analog Input A0
#define Offset 0.33     // deviation compensate

unsigned long int avgValue;  // Save the average values of the sensor
float b;
int buf[10], temp;

//Pin assignments for DFRobot LCD Keypad Shield
LiquidCrystal lcd(8, 9, 4, 5, 6, 7); 
//---------------------------------------------

void setup() {
  //LCD configuration
  lcd.begin(16, 2); // row and lines
  lcd.clear();
  lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
  lcd.print("senseBox Group 2018");
  lcd.setCursor(1, 1);
  lcd.print("  PH");
// scroll 13 positions (string length) to the left
  // to move it offscreen left:
  for (int positionCounter = 0; positionCounter < 13; positionCounter++) {
    // scroll one position left:
    lcd.scrollDisplayLeft();
    // wait a bit:
    delay(300);
  }
  pinMode(13, OUTPUT);  
}

void loop() {

  for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {     // Take 10 measurements to average 
    buf[i] = analogRead(SensorPin);
    delay(10);
  }

  for(int i = 0; i < 9; i++) {      // sort the measured values by height
    for(int j = i+1; j < 10; j++) {
      if(buf[i] > buf[j]) {
        temp = buf[i];
        buf[i] = buf[j];
        buf[j] = temp;
      }
    }
  }

   // Take the mean 6 readings and calculate the mean
  avgValue = 0;
  for(int i = 2; i < 8; i++) {                     
    avgValue += buf[i];
  }

  // Conversion of the input value in millivolts
  float voltage = (float)avgValue * 5.0 / 1024 / 6;
  // Conversion of the value of millivolts into the pH scale
  float phValue = 3.5 * voltage + Offset;

  Serial.print("    pH:");  
  Serial.print(phValue, 2);
  Serial.println(" ");
  lcd.clear();
  lcd.setCursor(0, 0);
  lcd.print("PH: ");
  lcd.print(phValue, 2);
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH);       
  delay(800);
  digitalWrite(13, LOW);

  delay(800);
}
